title: For Sale/Trade:  Looking to trade quadcopter parts DJI F450 kit, controllers, GPS, gamera gimble, etc. for firearms, or cash.
postcontent:
I purchased this from RC-drones.com as the DJI F450 about ready to fly kit.  It came with the main board, the DJI motors, and ESC controllers.  I bought exteneded landing gear for the camera gimble.  DJI NAZA controller.  Zenmuse H3-2D Gamera gimble.  DJI naza VMU.  iosd Mini(on screen display). NAZA GPS.    

I also purchased two controllers that you can see.   One is a Turnigy 9X and the other is the one out of the box the 9Xr.  Neither have been used, the other has not been out of the box.   I purchased a long range system for it.   Transmitter and receiver.  One is installed in the radio the other on the aircraft.  

This will come with 4 batteries.   3 DJI phantom batteries and a turnigy battery.

Fat shark antenaes are included.   For a FPV set up that is not included.

2 sets of different length blades.

I'm also throwing in a video recorder for someone who wants to do FPV.  You hook this to goggles or a monitor and it records anything you see.  Comes with a belt carrying case, a remote control, and all the cables.

Nothing has been powered up.   The board was soddered and the motors and esc's were put on.   the other parts are either loose or velcro'd on.   I was mocking everything up.   

If you look on the rc-drones website all of this gear cost over 2K  to purchase.  This can be a cheap way to get some of the best parts available for someone who already is into FPV drone flying, or someone who wants to go deeper into it.  My loss is your gain.   

Everything listed is brand new never been used except the batteries that have around 2-5 charge cycles on them in other craft.

Most of this stuff came with very few directions(as does most RC stuff).  I'm including what came with them.  All of the orignal packaging is gone for the most part except what you might see.   Youtube has examples of installing every single piece of EQ listed.

The cash price will be 950.   Putting the trade value closer to 2K depending on what we come up with.  If there is cash involved with firearms I will be a lot easier to negotiate with.

French 1873: I am not super familiar with the action of these revolvers, although I have read they use the "Chamelot-Delvigne" design. When this one is in its "resting state" the cylinder will rotate somewhat. To give you a rough idea, it will rotate approximately slightly more than the length of a bolt stop notch and preceding lead. However in both single action and in double action it seems to line up the cylinder about where it should be. Testing it like I would an old Colt, when the trigger is pulled, after the hammer falls, and the trigger remains pulled back, there is roughly a millimeter in movement in the play of the cylinder. I am guessing this is all normal but since I dont know I want to disclose it. Some strawing remains as shown. Note that these guns were produced "in the white." I have seen a number that people have blued, or even nickeled. I am calling it the german revolver a "reichsrevolver" and I hope that this terminology is correct. If not, please feel free to correct me.

German Model 1883 (Suhl): Not much to say on this one although I wanted to point out that it appears that the cylinder pin has a different number on it than the rest of the gun shows so I will assume it is a replacement from some point. Finish as shown, some bluing remains in protected areas.

I have not disassembled, or modified these guns in anyway (other than what I did for pictures), and am selling exactly as found. Please have inspected by gunsmith prior to shooting, and know that these are black powder guns not safe for modern cartridges.

TERMS: I would like $1k OBO for either one of them, or $1800 for the pair. 15$ for shipping. I accept usps money order, cashiers check, or other pre-agreed upon arrangements. I know that I can send the French as an antique because it was made in 1879. I will only need a copy of your driver's license to verify age of 21 or older, and a written/signed statement verifying that you are allowed to own this item. While I feel relatively confident the 1883 is classified as antique, I am told some WERE made after 1898. At this point I have not been able to verify age of this revolver and thus will be shipping to FFL. I will send it to C&R but shipping will be more since I am not allowed to ship handguns to C&R through post office. (Yes I know this is a debated topic but its how I run my business based on my understanding of PO regulations, thank you for your understanding!)

More pics upon request.

title: For Sale:  Swiss Model 1871 Vetterli Stutzer
location: Lake Villa, IL, Illinois, United States
postcontent:
This is a RARE M1871 Vetterli "STUTZER" model. These hardly ever come up on Gunbroker - haven't seen one for sale in the past several years. 

Unlike the stnadard 1871 Vetterli, the 1871 Vetterli Stutzer model is distinguished by the double set triggers. 


Some additional info about the Vetterli M1871 STUTZER: 

The Stutzer (carbine) variant of the 1871 rifle was used to equip the Scharfschützen (sniper) companies of the army. The Stutzer were equipped with a sensitive Stecher (double set trigger) action and featured a shorter barrel.

The 1871 Stutzer  incorporated several modifications over the 1869/71 and was intended for riflemen.  The 1871 included double-set triggers and special heavy buttplates.  The rifles were shorter, and had a single barrel band.  Early Stutzer models used the Thury dual trigger set, however, after 1875 a dual trigger set designed by Rudolph Schmidt was adopted.   However, while the Stutzer possessed a shorter barrel, it kept the Model 1869s rear sights.  This produced a point of impact error at when using the rear sights range graduations. 


Specs:

Barrel Length: 30.9 inches 
Overall Length: 49.6 inches 
Weight: 10.2 lbs empty 
Chambering: 10.4x38 (.41) Swiss Rimfire
Rifling: 4 groove, RH twist, 1 in 26" 
Velocity: 1375 fps 
Capacity: 11 (10 round tube magazine +1 in the cartridge elevator) 
Caliber/Ammo: 41 Swiss Rimfire 10.4xR38mm

Additional Details: 

1. Original, ALL matching SN 5331 on receiver, barrel, lifter, bolt, fore-end cap and fore-end wood.
2. Date of Manufacture: 1873 (aproximiately 7,500 for that year) Approximately 16,000 produced in all.
2. Arsenal: Eidgenössische Montier-Werstätte and Eidgenössische Waffenfabrik, Bern
3. Completely original. Has not been restored.
5. Beautiful old patina
6. Lands are sharp

The Bad:

1. The preivous owner at one point had converted the bolt to centerfire. Would NOT recommend firing. I know a guy in Flordia that can convert the bolt back to it's original Rimfire  configuration for $50.
2. Missing: Rear sling swivel (about $20-30 when the come up on Ebay) and Rod

This is a beautiful and rare 1871 Vetterli Stutzer. 

Forr sale for $850 OBO or TRADE!  I'm open to any/all trades. Shoot me an email if you're looking to trade.
